---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Fleet Tracking & Job Dispatch System | All Webbed Labs",
  metaDescription: "How we helped a Sydney courier company track 45 vehicles in real time, cut dispatcher call volume by 64%, and reduce average delivery times by 18% with a purpose-built dispatch and driver app.",

  industry: "Logistics & Transport",
  tags: ["Fleet Management", "Real-time Dispatch", "Driver App", "Route Optimisation", "Chain of Responsibility"],

  title: "Fleet Tracking & Job Dispatch System",
  summary: "A Sydney metropolitan courier company managing 45 vehicles and 52 drivers was running dispatch from a whiteboard and a phone — no GPS, no ETAs, and a ringing phone every time a corporate client wanted to know where their package was. We built a real-time dispatch dashboard and driver app that changed how the whole operation worked.",

  heroImageDescription: "Split-screen showing a dispatcher's web dashboard with live vehicle positions on a Sydney map alongside the Flutter driver app displaying the active job, route, and signature capture screen",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Arrow Express is a metropolitan courier company based in Sydney's inner west, operating a mixed fleet of 38 vans and 7 motorbikes with 52 drivers on the books across full-time, part-time, and contractor arrangements. The company serves primarily legal and medical clients — law firms requiring urgent document runs, medical centres with pathology transport, and corporate accounts needing same-day CBD delivery. Average daily job volume runs to 380 to 420 deliveries.",
  clientSize: "52 drivers, 45 vehicles, 380–420 deliveries/day",
  clientLocation: "Sydney, NSW",

  pullQuote: "The whiteboard worked fine when we had 15 vans. At 45, it just wasn't possible to hold the whole operation in your head. The dispatchers were doing incredible mental gymnastics every day and we were still dropping the ball on ETAs. Now everything is just... visible.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Marcus Webb",
  pullQuoteRole: "Operations Manager, Arrow Express",

  challenge: [
    "Dispatch at Arrow Express had evolved organically over twelve years. When the company started, one dispatcher knew every driver, every client, and every regular route. That knowledge was tacit and personal — it lived in the dispatcher's head, was reinforced by a whiteboard covered in magnetic name tags and coloured tape, and worked reasonably well up to about 20 drivers. By the time we were engaged, there were 45 vehicles on the road, three dispatchers working in rotation, and the whiteboard had become a source of daily confusion rather than clarity.",
    "The absence of GPS tracking was the root of most operational problems. Dispatchers had no reliable way to know where any given vehicle was at any point in time. They knew where drivers had been assigned and roughly how long the route should take, but Sydney traffic is not predictable, and a driver stuck on the M4 after an incident had no practical way to communicate their delay beyond a phone call — which the dispatcher would then have to relay to the client, who might have already called twice asking for an ETA. On a day with 420 jobs, dispatchers were fielding 60 to 80 ETA calls before lunch.",
    "Proof of delivery was entirely paper-based. Drivers carried a job sheet for each delivery — a carbonless duplicate form with recipient name, address, and a signature line. The top copy stayed with the recipient; the bottom copy returned to the office at the end of the driver's shift. For the firm's legal clients, proof of delivery documentation was not optional: law firms filing documents with courts and serving legal process needed to be able to demonstrate that a document had been received, by whom, and at what time. Paper dockets returned at end of shift were scanned and filed manually, and any docket that came back illegible or damaged created a compliance problem.",
    "Chain of Responsibility obligations under the Heavy Vehicle National Law — even though Arrow's vehicles were under the 4.5-tonne threshold, they operated in regulated environments with clients who imposed their own CoR documentation requirements — meant Arrow needed to be able to demonstrate that delivery times, vehicle conditions, and driver fatigue management were managed and recorded. The paper system couldn't produce any of this retrospectively in a structured, auditable format. After a client — a major law firm — raised documentation concerns following a disputed delivery, the operations manager decided it was time to change.",
    "Route efficiency was a daily inefficiency that nobody had the bandwidth to optimise. Each morning, dispatchers printed job lists and assigned runs to drivers based on geographic clusters and experience. There was no routing algorithm involved; it was pattern-matching based on familiarity with Sydney suburbs. On some days the matching was good; on others, two drivers would cross each other's paths at significant cost in time and fuel. Without GPS data, there was no way to measure how inefficient the routing actually was, which meant there was no pressure to improve it."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "Arrow Express came to us via a referral from another transport business in the same industrial precinct that had used us for a simpler delivery management project two years earlier. The operations manager had looked at two off-the-shelf fleet management platforms — both well-established products with GPS tracking and basic dispatch features — but both required a per-vehicle monthly subscription that, at 45 vehicles, added up to a cost that the business wasn't comfortable with for features they'd only partially use. More importantly, neither platform had a driver app that worked offline for the city fringe and outer suburb runs where mobile data could be patchy.",
    "What sealed the decision was a conversation about the law firm client relationship. The operations manager wanted the platform to generate delivery records that could be produced to a client in legal proceedings — timestamped, with GPS coordinates, recipient name, and a captured digital signature. Off-the-shelf products could produce reports, but the format and audit trail weren't structured in a way that would satisfy a solicitor's documentary standards. We'd done similar work for a medical transport company and understood the documentation requirements. That prior experience made the difference."
  ],

  approach: [
    "We ran a three-day discovery sprint with Arrow Express before writing any code. Day one was spent with the dispatchers — watching how jobs were allocated, understanding the priority hierarchy (legal document runs always trumped general corporate deliveries; pathology samples had a hard time window), and mapping the information a dispatcher needed at any moment to make good allocation decisions. Day two was spent riding along with two drivers through their full shifts to understand the driver experience: how they navigate, how they communicate with dispatch, what information they need at the start of a job and at the point of delivery. Day three was reviewing the paper proof of delivery system and the law firm's specific documentation requirements.",
    "The dispatcher dashboard and the driver app were always conceived as two halves of the same system — information flows in both directions, and the design had to serve both the person making decisions at a desk and the person executing them from a vehicle cab. We prototyped the dispatcher's map view early and tested it with all three dispatchers, establishing the right balance of information density: enough to see the full fleet picture at a glance without the map becoming unreadable.",
    "Technology choice for the driver app was straightforward once we'd confirmed the offline requirement. Flutter gave us a single codebase for iOS and Android, which mattered because Arrow's driver fleet used a mix of both platforms (some drivers used their own phones; the company was issuing Android devices to the remaining drivers). React Native was also on our shortlist but Flutter's offline data persistence story and its performance on lower-end Android devices — some drivers were on older Oppos and Samsungs — gave it the edge.",
    "The routing integration used Google Maps Directions API for route optimisation. We evaluated HERE Routing API as an alternative but Google Maps' Sydney-specific traffic and road data was more current, particularly for construction closures and CBD access restrictions that change frequently. The routing suggestions are presented to dispatchers as recommendations, not mandates — a deliberate design decision to preserve dispatcher expertise and override capability rather than automating allocation in a way that would remove human judgement from edge cases."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The dispatcher dashboard is a real-time map view of the full Arrow fleet, updated via WebSocket every 15 seconds from GPS data sent by the driver app. Each vehicle on the map shows the driver's name, current status (en route to pickup, at pickup, en route to delivery, at delivery, available), and the number of remaining jobs in their queue. Clicking a vehicle opens a panel showing their full job list, current ETA to next delivery, and a contact button that opens a pre-filled SMS rather than requiring the dispatcher to find the driver's number.",
    "Job allocation works by dragging jobs from an unallocated queue on the left panel onto a driver on the map or in the driver list. When a job is allocated, the driver receives an immediate push notification on their app with the pickup address, delivery address, and any special instructions. The app queues jobs in order and uses the Google Directions API to calculate the optimal route sequence. Drivers can re-sequence their own queue within limits — they can't remove jobs or change delivery addresses, but they can swap the order of jobs with similar ETAs if they know the local streets better than the algorithm.",
    "The driver app is built around a clean, single-job focus. The driver sees one job at a time — the active job — with a large 'Navigate' button that opens Google Maps with the destination pre-loaded and a 'Arrived' button to confirm they're at the delivery address. On arrival confirmation, the app opens the delivery screen: a signature pad, a mandatory photo capture (camera opens automatically), and a recipient name field. Completed deliveries are submitted immediately over the mobile data connection, or queued for background sync if the connection is unavailable.",
    "Customer notifications are sent automatically via Twilio SMS at two trigger points: when a driver is allocated to a job (a 'your delivery has been dispatched' message with an estimated arrival window), and when the driver marks themselves as en route to the delivery address after completing the preceding job (a 'your driver is 15–20 minutes away' message, calculated from the real-time ETA). These two messages replaced the majority of ETA inquiry calls. Law firm clients, in particular, used the real-time ETA message to brief a receptionist to be ready for a process server delivery.",
    "Chain of Responsibility reporting is handled through an automated end-of-day report generated at 10pm each night. The report covers fleet activity — kilometres driven, active hours per driver, job completion rates — and flags any deliveries where the GPS trail showed more than 30 minutes of idle time in a single location (a potential indicator of a break that should be logged for fatigue management purposes). This report is generated as a PDF and emailed to the operations manager automatically; unusual items are flagged in red. Arrow's compliance documentation is now fully automated rather than assembled manually."
  ],

  implementation: [
    "We delivered the dispatcher dashboard and driver app together in a single eight-week build, with a staged rollout. The first two weeks of live operation used a pilot group of ten drivers — the operations manager's most technically comfortable team members — running the app alongside the existing paper process. This parallel-run period caught several driver UX issues that hadn't emerged in internal testing: the signature pad was too small on 5-inch phone screens (we increased the capture area), and the photo requirement on delivery caused friction when drivers were handing over to a reception desk with a queue of people behind them (we added a 'lobby delivery' mode that captures a photo of the front desk rather than requiring a recipient in-frame).",
    "Full fleet rollout was completed over a single week after the pilot. We held two 45-minute training sessions — one for day-shift drivers, one for afternoon-shift — at the depot before the Monday launch, and were on-site for the first two full working days to handle real-time issues. Driver adoption was higher than expected; most drivers were on smartphones already and found the app straightforward. The biggest adaptation was for three drivers who had been with the company for over eight years and had strong opinions about route sequencing — for those drivers, we made sure the manual re-sequencing feature was prominently explained.",
    "The WebSocket server required careful capacity planning for the 45-vehicle simultaneous connection scenario. We deployed on AWS using ECS with an Application Load Balancer configured for WebSocket pass-through, and load tested to 80 simultaneous connections (nearly double the current fleet) before go-live. In production, the system has remained well within those limits and connection stability has been strong across both 4G and wifi connections."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The offline sync behaviour of the driver app needed more real-world testing than we gave it in staging. Sydney's cellular coverage is generally good, but a handful of underground car parks in the CBD — where law firm offices often have loading docks — have no signal at all. A delivery completed in an underground car park would queue for sync, but if the driver moved to their next pickup before surfacing, the queue could hold multiple items in an ambiguous state. We added an explicit 'pending sync' indicator on the app's main screen and an automatic retry on reconnect, but the lesson is to test sync edge cases in the actual physical environments the product will be used in.",
    "Google Maps ETA accuracy in Sydney CBD varied significantly by time of day in ways our initial testing hadn't fully captured. ETAs calculated in the morning before peak hour were consistently optimistic for CBD deliveries during the 8am–9:30am window. We added a time-of-day adjustment factor for CBD postcodes during the peak window, calibrated from two weeks of actual ETA versus actual arrival data collected in the pilot. This reduced ETA error from an average of 9 minutes late to 3 minutes late for peak-CBD deliveries.",
    "We had assumed dispatchers would embrace the algorithmic job allocation suggestions enthusiastically. In practice, the most experienced dispatcher — who had been with Arrow for seven years — treated the routing suggestions as a starting point that she often overrode based on knowledge we hadn't captured: which buildings had difficult loading docks, which clients needed their jobs done before a specific internal deadline, which drivers had established relationships with particular clients. Her overrides were consistently better than the algorithm's suggestions for those specific cases. The lesson is that automation in dispatch enhances experienced operators; it doesn't replace their knowledge."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Eight months post-launch, Arrow Express expanded their fleet by six vehicles and onboarded two new corporate clients. The operations manager noted that the expansion was possible in large part because the platform meant the additional complexity didn't require adding a fourth dispatcher — the existing team of three could handle the larger fleet because the information they needed was now visible rather than having to be held in memory.",
    "The company is exploring adding a client web portal — a read-only view for their law firm and corporate accounts to track active deliveries in real time and access their delivery history. This would further reduce the inbound calls that still occasionally come from accounts who want to track a time-sensitive delivery themselves. We've scoped this as a relatively straightforward extension of the existing data model, with the main work being around access control to ensure clients can only see their own jobs."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "The results below were measured over the first six months of full fleet operation. Delivery time reduction is a median across all jobs, comparing job allocation timestamp to delivery completion timestamp. Dispatcher call volume data comes from Arrow's phone system logs. Fuel cost data was provided by the operations manager based on monthly fuel card statements.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "−18%", label: "Average delivery time", context: "Median time from job allocation to delivery completion" },
    { value: "−64%", label: "Dispatcher call volume", context: "ETA inquiries replaced by automated SMS notifications" },
    { value: "45", label: "Vehicles tracked in real time", context: "Full fleet visible to dispatchers at all times" },
    { value: "−11%", label: "Fuel costs", context: "From route optimisation across the full fleet" },
    { value: "4.4/5", label: "Customer satisfaction rating", context: "Up from 3.6 — based on quarterly client survey" },
    { value: "100%", label: "CoR documentation compliance", context: "Automated end-of-day reports replaced manual assembly" }
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Dispatcher dashboard with real-time map view and job management interface" },
    { name: "Flutter", reason: "Cross-platform driver app for iOS and Android with offline-first data persistence" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "Backend API and WebSocket server for real-time GPS position broadcasting" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Job records, delivery history, GPS trail data, and driver activity logs" },
    { name: "Google Maps API", reason: "Map rendering, geocoding, and live traffic-adjusted routing" },
    { name: "Google Directions API", reason: "Multi-stop route optimisation with real-time traffic adjustment" },
    { name: "WebSockets", reason: "Real-time bidirectional communication between driver app and dispatcher dashboard" },
    { name: "Twilio SMS", reason: "Automated customer ETA notifications at dispatch and en-route trigger points" },
    { name: "AWS (ECS, RDS, S3)", reason: "Containerised deployment with load balancing for WebSocket connections" },
    { name: "PDF generation", reason: "Automated chain of responsibility and end-of-day compliance reports" }
  ],

